review_blob: Bottle; pours clear light amber with a small head; nice mellow hop and bitterness; very yeasty aroma as it warms; EGF 1. (#64)
Bottle; go read Dead Guy and add a bit more bitterness; I agree with Rustyham, go drink Dead Guy instead. (#63)

Bottle; white head; awesome balance between the malt, rye and hop that leaned a little to the malt; recommended by SR from Central Market .. glad I listened; rye bitterness mouthfeel is unique; a definite repeat purchase. EGF 2. (#62)
Bottle; pours a solid murky deep gold to light amber; white medium head; nice balance between the hop and spices. EGF 1 (#61)
Bottle; very strong hop; clear red brown pour; not for the faint of heart; stay away if your not a hop head. (#60)
beer_name: Moylans Hopsickle Imperial India Pale Ale

review_blob: Bottle; clear fuzzy head; haze gold pour; slight carbonation; slight aroma of citrus. EFG 1; hints of hop around palate but not on initial intake; no citrus or fruit on palate but slightly in the flavor but not much flavor otherwise. (#59)

Bottle; not what I was expecting; dark clear copper pour; foamy head; typical aroma; EFG 1; lots of carbonation; nice malt flavor with a slight bitter hop taste; as it warms the alcoholic aroma and flavor really kicks in. (#58)
22oz bottle; medium to hi carbonation; pours copper amber; EGF 3.5; big white foamy head; smell of hop, grass and citrus; hoppy bitterness; bitter carbonated mouthfeel. (#57)
beer_name: Laughing Dog Alpha Dog Imperial IPA

review_blob: Bottle; pours light brown; thick caramel color head; a bit oxidized; hints of a flat carbonation with a warming spice; EFG3. (#56)
Bottle; easy to drink with mild malt and not hoppy; a bit of a carbonated mouthfeel; nice organic safe beer. (#55)
330ml bottle (Commemorative Ale bottle); syrupy; big foamy head; better then average second beer of the night. (#54)
beer_name: Hitachino Nest New Year Celebration Ale

review_blob: 12oz bottle; poured a clear dark amber; white head that dissipated fast; nice malt that didnt overpower the palate; EGF 1. (#53)
beer_name: Flying Dog Old Scratch Amber Lager

review_blob: Tap at Northgate; nice roast and smoky in flavor; very tasty; poured dark brown to light black; a definite reorder. (#52)
Tap at Tangletown; not a complex bitterness, very relaxed; more malty then I expected and a bit flat. (#51)

Bottle; crazy soy sauce aroma; dark caramel head; medium body; pours dark except around the edges; I never really got the traditional chocolate or cream but found it to be syrupy and sticky; had bitterness like you would find in bakers chocolate; just not too crazy about this one. (#50)
12oz bottle; not too hoppy; nice starter beer for the evening; this would be a good craft to have on hand for those new to this type of beer. (#49)
Tap at Northgate; seasonal; thick and creamy head due to the nitro; coffee and roast at the finish; no flavor what so ever up front; just a standard stout. (#48)
Tap; sweet and slightly malty; poured medium yellow; just o.k. (#47)
Tap; attractive cloudiness; decent; pours deep gold to light amber. (#46)

22oz bottle; initials pours as a slightly hazed red/brown amber but then gets real clear while retaining its caramel tinted head; aromatic hop aroma and astringent flavor; peaks of dry bitter with a mellowed hop. (#45)
Tap; good bitterness not to sharp; assertive citrus but doesnt overpower; nice copper amber appearance. (#44)
Tap; smooth to slightly sweet finish; easy to drink but a forgettable beer. (#43)
Tap at Tangletown; refreshing, hoppy, and strong; slight spice in the back; nice lace. (#42)
Tap at Tangletown; very dark full body; thick lace; very balanced malt to hop with hints of smoke; enjoyable without being overpowering. (#41)
Bottle; medium black pour with hints of ruby; very floral aroma with traces of molasses; not much flavor; forgettable. (#40)
Tap; deep straw to gold in color; rich sweet malt; standard lackluster mai. (#39)

Tap at Tangletown; enjoyable dark wheat beer; poured brownish with amber tones; my palate and vision was probably getting skewed at this point but I really enjoyed it on this cold sunny Meridian day. (#38)

Tap; tones of semi sweet chocolate and roasted coffee finish; poured midnight black; decent roasted aroma which matches the balanced roasted flavor; good mouth coating malty body; a standout amongst their other brews. (#37)

Tap at Tangletown; Cask Conditioned; great aroma - very fruity; nice balanced hop mid palate; faint citrus bitterness resides throughout palate; has a bit of w.o.w. factor to it; kinda feel joyous getting a chance to embrace this beer. (#36)
Bottle 12oz; just enough sweetness from the fruit to make it enjoyable; medium body; balanced bitter and malt that works well with the fruit; hoppy/acidic remains through digestion. (#35)
Brewpub tap; aggressive hop flavor; poured light copper with a medium body; has a nice balance that washes over the palate; tad bit acidic to bitter at times. (#34)

Brewpub tap; advertised as a crisp grapefruit flavor but I didnt taste much of the grapefruit but did pickup on the bitterness normally associated with the grapefruit; decent safe beer; also had a Nitro Sequoia Red which made the head really pop and cut down on the bitterness a bit; a bit more enjoyable; I rate the nitro as 3.4. (#33)
Brewpub tap; dull bitterness; hints of caramel; herbal hop flavor; very straightforward beer. (#32)

Brewpub tap; similar to their IPA but much more hoppy which pretty much killed the grapefruit undertones; have had other beers with high hop and grapefruit that pulled it off better; will have to try this one again while not having their IPA beforehand. (#31)
beer_name: Diamond Knot Industrial India Pale Ale

review_blob: Brewpub tap; faint lemon over the palate; nice flavor going down with a clean finish; would be a good to quench the thirst on a warm day. (#30)
Brewpub tap; malty with citrus undertones that are not as strong as a normal hef; poured a nice straw color; little bit of a disappointment. (#29)
Tap at Lincoln Ave; nice balance between the bitterness and malt; they use Galena and Williamette hops in this one; pours black with tones of red; tasty. (#28)
Tap at Lincoln Ave; pours near red brown with a nice malt flavor that quenches the thirst; their early spring seasonal on tap now; creamy head with a sweet caramel finish. (#27)
beer_name: Diamond Knot Slanes Irish Style Ale

review_blob: Tap from Lincoln Ave location; nice mello bitterness with hints of grapefruit and traces of cedar; canyon wall lacing; brewed with Columbus hops. (#26)
22oz bottle; not much that stayed with the palate; big foamy head; balanced in flavor but didnt sway to one side for any enjoyability; sporadic sloppy lace; medium to light amber. (#25)

12oz bottle; cream soda color head; solid mid amber in color; aroma varied pine with big punches of grapefruit; flavor matched exactly to the aroma; bold in taste while there was a happy medium between the grapefruit and bitterness; really enjoyed this one. (#24)
12 bottle; pours clear light amber to orange, bubbly head that quickly dissipated; not an overpowering pilsner; nothing special. (#23)
12oz bottle; typical barley wine flavor with mellow floral  and hints of bitter; nothing to much more to boast about. (#22)
Tap; very floral aroma and opaque yellow in color served w/ a lemon; definitely could stand alone; worth the purchase. (#21)
Tap; maintained dark amber throughout; very balanced smooth hop flavor from beginning to end; a definite reorder. (#20)

Bottle; subtle chocolate aroma; nice balance of chocolate hints that flows over the palate without overpowering; felt at times I would taste tiny pockets of cocoa powder which kept me intrigued with it. (#19)
Draft @ Powerhouse; nice deep ruby color and very cherry syrupy aroma; very complex flavor that kept me second guessing on what I was tasting; very unique. (#18)
Tap; strange aroma - almost like if you were at a bath house thats part of a large camp ground; looks water but easy to drink; unique to say the least. (#17)

beer_brewer_name: Hair of the Dog Brewing Company
review_blob: 12oz bottle; big sediment heavy body; get mesmerized by watching all the sediment; pours dark yellow with a small head; nice citrus over the palate; for me a great beer to keep stocked for the days Im in the mood for an unfiltered APA. (#16)
Tap; sweet hop but not as hoppy as most pale ales; is balanced if you dont like alot of hop; however very drinkable. (#15)
